Heart-crushing news to learn that @jimmybuffett’s gone. He was a close friend for almost 40 years. Nobody had more pure fun in life, or worked harder to share it with others. He lived true to his songs, and he was writing with joy until the end, tweaking the final cuts on a new album. Jimmy had one gear: moving at the speed of light, even in flip-flops. He was, literally and exuberantly, all over the map. Richly talented, wonderfully generous, and wildly passionate about the places he cherished – peaceful islands and harbors where he transported everyone who loved his music. Still he was happiest on stage, whether it was a bar in Key West or center field at Fenway Park. I’d like to think that somewhere is a pristine stretch of Caribbean beach where we still might find – propped against a palm tree -- a fly rod and a Martin guitar. And, riding the waves, a familiar bionic pirate on a long board, grinning about all the cool shit he got away with. I’ll miss you, JB. Millions will. Thanks for the laughs, the adventures, and the unforgettable sound track.
Air Buffett, way back in the day.

RIP Capt. John Kipp, 1955-2023.
John was a great bonefish and tarpon guide, a longtime friend, and an authentically wild Florida Keys character. Over the years, his true-life antics inspired several scenes in my novels – some funny, some scary, some purely outrageous. John was all those things. He was also a fierce conservationist who loved the Keys and Florida Bay, and worked closely with Florida Audubon and other groups fighting to save the wild habitats of native birds and gamefish. He and I spent many unforgettable days in his skiff, fishing the flats of Islamorada or the back country of Everglades Natural Park. That’s where John was at his happiest, and most at peace….until some dumbass on a Jet Ski cut across the bank. Then anything could happen, and all you could do was hold your breath. John was legendary for holding fellow humans accountable, in his own way. You could fill a book with all the stories. I’ll miss him. He was a presence.

Here’s the description of WRECKER:

Wrecker needs to deal with smugglers, grave robbers, and pooping iguanas—just as soon as he finishes Zoom school. Welcome to another wild adventure in Carl Hiaasen's Florida!

Valdez Jones VIII calls himself Wrecker because his great-great-great-great-great-grandfather salvaged shipwrecks for a living. 

So is it destiny, irony, or just bad luck when Wrecker comes across a speedboat that has run hard aground on a sand flat? The men in the boat don't want Wrecker to call for help—in fact, they'll pay him to forget he ever saw them. 

Wrecker would be happy to forget, but he keeps seeing these men all over Key West—at the marina, in the cemetery, even right outside his own door. And now they want more than his silence—they want a lookout.

He'll have to dive deep into their shady dealings to figure out a way to escape this tangled net. . . .

These are @jimmybuffett's hand-written notes for "Fish Porn," a song on his new album, "Equal Strain on All Parts." The phrase "fish porn" refers to fishermen texting photos or videos of themselves showing off a big catch. Jimmy thought it was funny enough for a song title, and we started playing around with it about a year ago in the Bahamas. My contribution was only a handful of lyrics, but Jimmy generously gave me a writing credit. Watching him and @macmcanally work their magic on the song was very cool.

GIVING NATURE A VOICE, by Carl Hiaasen 

It was a huge honor when Carl Hiaasen (@carl_hiaasen) agreed to write the foreword of my book, Path of the Panther, published this year by National Geographic. Below are a few of his magical words. Please check out the whole essay at the beginning of the book. 

It is fitting that he writes about his only wild panther sighting across from a photo of the only panther I’ve ever seen in the wild while actually holding a camera in my hand. 

“The mythic aura of the Florida panther is well deserved. The cats are heart-stoppingly beautiful and famously elusive, apex phantoms on the run from mad suburban sprawl…

…This book places you right there, nose to nose with a spectral predator that spends every waking hour trying not to be seen. The glimpses captured in Ward’s photographs justify our awe of panthers and make more compelling the fight to forever secure the places where they still run wild, gloriously out of sight.”

Visit wildpath.com/book to learn more, and find Path of the Panther at your favorite book store. Your purchase helps me and the @wildpath team and continue to use this story to help save land in the Florida Wildlife Corridor.

Happy New Year’s greetings from Florida, where we await the pouty return of Gov. Ron DeSantis as soon as he drops out of the presidential race. Our thoughts and prayers go out to the good people in all 99 counties of Iowa, who stoically endured visit after tedious visit from DeSantis in advance of the GOP caucuses. You folks never backed down! Soon you’ll be free to answer your front doors without fear of being bored into a coma by chatty campaign workers. No longer will your livestock be startled by the sound of DeSantis’ private jet flying low over your pastures and cornfields. Red Tide Ronnie will be back in Florida soon, and he won’t be happy. Please keep us in your hearts during 2024, which will undoubtedly be another embarrassing year for the Sunshine State. Meanwhile, if any Moms for Liberty invite you to a “very private” New Year’s Eve party, just say no.

”If you could use some wild escapism right now, Hiaasen is your guy.” 
—The New York Times
